00:41:59.710 --> 00:42:02.464
Do you go use [INAUDIBLE]
for stuff like this?

00:42:02.464 --> 00:42:04.130
I would love to learn
a little bit more.

00:42:04.130 --> 00:42:05.430
ROMAN MARS: Yeah.

00:42:05.430 --> 00:42:16.300
So I mostly use a shotgun
mic and AT897 to track.

00:42:16.300 --> 00:42:21.040
It's not the prescribed
use, to do vocal voiceovers.

00:42:21.040 --> 00:42:21.960
It's the one I had.

00:42:24.800 --> 00:42:27.600
It was the one I had.

00:42:27.600 --> 00:42:29.220
It's one of the
reasons why it sounds

00:42:29.220 --> 00:42:31.700
so close is because I
mike it really close, off

00:42:31.700 --> 00:42:33.450
my face a little bit.

00:42:33.450 --> 00:42:38.610
And it's a shotgun mic
and a normal vocal.

00:42:38.610 --> 00:42:39.975
We write in Google Docs.

00:42:43.400 --> 00:42:46.880
We share in group.

00:42:46.880 --> 00:42:50.320
Once a person gets a certain
amount, they open it up.

00:42:50.320 --> 00:42:54.350
Especially Katie who-- she
only shares at a certain point

00:42:54.350 --> 00:42:56.290
because she has grading.

00:42:56.290 --> 00:42:58.310
If somebody can see
her typing poorly,

00:42:58.310 --> 00:43:01.310
she gets really
anxious about that.

00:43:01.310 --> 00:43:04.340
So she only shares it
after a certain point

00:43:04.340 --> 00:43:08.300
and then we work together
on the Google Doc.

00:43:08.300 --> 00:43:10.820
Even in a room, we'll
play the thing out loud

00:43:10.820 --> 00:43:13.770
and we're all making comments
in the comment stream.

00:43:17.320 --> 00:43:19.060
In the beginning, I
didn't use scripts.

00:43:19.060 --> 00:43:22.094
I mainly wrote on the fly.

00:43:22.094 --> 00:43:23.760
So in the beginning
when it was just me,

00:43:23.760 --> 00:43:30.050
I would have bullet points and
I would just play the clip,

00:43:30.050 --> 00:43:32.560
say what I was thinking, cut
it together in Pro Tools,

00:43:32.560 --> 00:43:35.300
and then write it in Pro Tools.

00:43:35.300 --> 00:43:37.210
In a way I could
write it in Pro Tools.

00:43:37.210 --> 00:43:39.600
And then if it didn't
work, or the breath was

00:43:39.600 --> 00:43:42.080
wrong or something, then
I'd re-perform the thing

00:43:42.080 --> 00:43:43.976
I cut together.

00:43:43.976 --> 00:43:45.600
And I used to call
that retroscripting.

00:43:45.600 --> 00:43:50.850
It was a way for it to sound
extemporaneous because it was.

00:43:50.850 --> 00:43:52.680
It was really me
reacting to the take.

00:43:52.680 --> 00:43:55.400
But it was tighter, and
I cut it and edited it,

00:43:55.400 --> 00:43:58.320
and I would just try it again
and again until I got it right.

00:43:58.320 --> 00:44:00.741
And so there were no
scripts in the beginning.

00:44:00.741 --> 00:44:02.740
But now when you have to
work with other people,

00:44:02.740 --> 00:44:04.520
you have to write
stuff down on paper.

00:44:04.520 --> 00:44:07.775
Or "paper."

00:44:07.775 --> 00:44:09.170
Yeah, is there anything else?

00:44:09.170 --> 00:44:10.385
And we'd work in Pro Tools.

00:44:10.385 --> 00:44:12.560
AUDIENCE: Just so you don't
have to use compression, EQ.

00:44:12.560 --> 00:44:13.268
ROMAN MARS: Yeah.

00:44:13.268 --> 00:44:22.340
So I use basic compression
inside of Pro Tools for me.

00:44:22.340 --> 00:44:25.340
I have a booming
middle, so I drop down

00:44:25.340 --> 00:44:29.490
the mid-range of my
voice so you can hear me

00:44:29.490 --> 00:44:31.910
over music or stuff.

00:44:31.910 --> 00:44:33.742
Sometimes I forget.

00:44:33.742 --> 00:44:35.700
So sometimes if you notice
it, and you're like,

00:44:35.700 --> 00:44:37.890
you sound really muddy and
when you're driving in a car

00:44:37.890 --> 00:44:40.181
I can't hear your voice at
all because it's all rumbly.

00:44:40.181 --> 00:44:42.612
But that's because I
didn't cut down the middle.

00:44:45.410 --> 00:44:46.610
Yeah, that's about it.

00:44:46.610 --> 00:44:47.610
We don't do a lot.

00:44:47.610 --> 00:44:51.760
A little bit of max and a
little bit of compression.

