feel that over time.

00:49:52.820 --> 00:49:55.280
I think there's
dangers of what that

00:49:55.280 --> 00:50:00.280
can do to you, like the
employee-employer relationship.

00:50:00.280 --> 00:50:04.844
I don't know what they do to
you, or what they make you do.

00:50:04.844 --> 00:50:06.510
But there's dangers
of that because when

00:50:06.510 --> 00:50:13.640
you get sequestered, like
when you're in college,

00:50:13.640 --> 00:50:15.450
you feel everything more.

00:50:15.450 --> 00:50:18.280
Because you're on this campus,
you feel the rage more.

00:50:18.280 --> 00:50:19.470
You feel the injustice more.

00:50:19.470 --> 00:50:23.120
You feel weird
slights about things.

00:50:23.120 --> 00:50:24.530
You feel it more.

00:50:24.530 --> 00:50:29.010
Maybe if you were
integrated into a city,

00:50:29.010 --> 00:50:30.840
it would have less
of that effect.

00:50:30.840 --> 00:50:36.260
And I always warn
people, when you

00:50:36.260 --> 00:50:41.340
take a job where they have
laundry facilities, that

00:50:41.340 --> 00:50:45.800
means they want you to be
there instead of at home doing

00:50:45.800 --> 00:50:46.610
your laundry.

00:50:46.610 --> 00:50:48.660
And so that's a choice.

00:50:48.660 --> 00:50:52.200
Sometimes that seems like
an awesome choice to me.

00:50:52.200 --> 00:50:57.140
But sometimes probably
it's not a good choice.

00:50:57.140 --> 00:51:00.840
So the environment
reflects those values.

00:51:00.840 --> 00:51:02.724
So it's just part of it.

00:51:02.724 --> 00:51:04.140
AUDIENCE: First
of all, thank you.

00:51:04.140 --> 00:51:07.880
We're on a shuttle for three
or four or five hours a day,

00:51:07.880 --> 00:51:13.320
and it's entertaining to listen
to you uncover these stories.

00:51:13.320 --> 00:51:15.195
But I was just
curious how much do

00:51:15.195 --> 00:51:20.320
you hold the concept of "99%
Invisible" to the stories

00:51:20.320 --> 00:51:22.700
that you guys create?

00:51:22.700 --> 00:51:26.260
Do you sometimes find yourself
saying, well, that's 20%?

00:51:26.260 --> 00:51:28.780
ROMAN MARS: Is 99
invisible enough?

00:51:28.780 --> 00:51:31.720
Yeah, I don't.

00:51:31.720 --> 00:51:34.610
We don't measure against
that sort of thing.

00:51:34.610 --> 00:51:36.320
AUDIENCE: Well,
because it very often

00:51:36.320 --> 00:51:39.030
seems like you're the guy
that reads the plaques

00:51:39.030 --> 00:51:42.110
and finds the stories
in the plaques.

00:51:42.110 --> 00:51:46.860
Do you ever find yourself
vetting the concept

00:51:46.860 --> 00:51:50.970
against some of the stories
that you're coming up with?

00:51:50.970 --> 00:51:54.660
ROMAN MARS: Yeah, a little bit.

00:51:54.660 --> 00:51:58.860
They're design stories
that are stories.

00:51:58.860 --> 00:52:01.090
We call them "dude
with a project"

00:52:01.090 --> 00:52:03.950
stories, which are cool
things that someone

00:52:03.950 --> 00:52:06.930
does that solves a problem.

00:52:06.930 --> 00:52:09.410
But it really
doesn't help you view

00:52:09.410 --> 00:52:11.030
the world in any different way.

00:52:11.030 --> 00:52:12.720
It just is interesting.

00:52:12.720 --> 00:52:16.470
And that to me is the equivalent
of arts reporting, of like,

00:52:16.470 --> 00:52:17.365
here's a good band.

00:52:17.365 --> 00:52:20.720
I want to tell you
about that band.

00:52:20.720 --> 00:52:23.590
I like the ones where
when you're done with it,

00:52:23.590 --> 00:52:26.300
you decode the world
in a different way.

00:52:26.300 --> 00:52:28.700
And that's usually what the
secret sauce that puts it

00:52:28.700 --> 00:52:30.577
over the edge for a
"99% Invisible" story.

00:52:30.577 --> 00:52:32.535
It doesn't have to be
the most invisible thing.

00:52:32.535 --> 00:52:35.820
In fact, for the most part, what
I love is the really obvious

00:52:35.820 --> 00:52:38.090
and ubiquitous things, and
going, no, wait a minute.

00:52:38.090 --> 00:52:39.050
Pay attention.

00:52:39.050 --> 00:52:41.760
There's an interesting
parts to this thing.

00:52:41.760 --> 00:52:44.860
Those are actually my
favorite types of stories.

00:52:44.860 --> 00:52:48.070
AUDIENCE: OK, so you've gone
from podcasting at night

00:52:48.070 --> 00:52:50.825
to making a full time job to now
creating business with a team.

00:52:50.825 --> 00:52:53.720
I think that's mainly through
the power of Kickstarter.

00:52:53.720 --> 00:52:55.487
ROMAN MARS: It's
one of them, yeah.

00:52:55.487 --> 00:52:56.820
AUDIENCE: I've been a supporter.

00:52:56.820 --> 00:53:00.115
ROMAN MARS: Yeah, no,
I appreciate that.

00:53:00.115 --> 00:53:01.740
AUDIENCE: And through
Radiotopia you're

00:53:01.740 --> 00:53:03.365
now giving that chance
to other people.

00:53:03.365 --> 00:53:06.090
Do you see the Kickstarter
and Patreon patronage model

00:53:06.090 --> 00:53:09.090
letting more people pursue their
artistic passion that same way

00:53:09.090 --> 00:53:11.137
and turning into
a job or something

00:53:11.137 --> 00:53:13.720
that they can support them, or
how do you see that developing?

00:53:13.720 --> 00:53:15.178
ROMAN MARS: Yeah,
well, Kickstarter

00:53:15.178 --> 00:53:16.800
was hugely important to me.

00:53:16.800 --> 00:53:21.220
I mean to me at the beginning
it was a means to an end.

00:53:21.220 --> 00:53:24.620
I needed money to survive or
it wasn't going to happen.

00:53:24.620 --> 00:53:26.590
The show wasn't going to exist.

00:53:26.590 --> 00:53:28.890
But what I didn't know,
because the first Kickstart

00:53:28.890 --> 00:53:33.720
took off in such a way and it
became the biggest journalism

00:53:33.720 --> 00:53:35.180
Kickstart at the time.

00:53:35.180 --> 00:53:37.440
And then we did again,
and became bigger.

00:53:40.010 --> 00:53:42.410
It became a story
in and of itself.

00:53:42.410 --> 00:53:51.680
And a lot of it was the vanguard
of a lot of this podcast,

00:53:51.680 --> 00:53:53.220
like resurgence at the time.

00:53:53.220 --> 00:53:57.950
I mean Alex Blumberg,
who does Gimlet,

00:53:57.950 --> 00:54:01.570
has very generously cited
me as some kind of influence

00:54:01.570 --> 00:54:04.110
in making his thing.

00:54:04.110 --> 00:54:08.280
It's not entirely true, but
he's sweet about that stuff.

00:54:08.280 --> 00:54:11.840
But realizing that you could
form a tight connection

00:54:11.840 --> 00:54:14.320
with your audience, and
they would value you

00:54:14.320 --> 00:54:17.470
more than the radio stations
we used to make things for

00:54:17.470 --> 00:54:21.390
was a huge deal to
us as producers.

00:54:21.390 --> 00:54:24.620
And for the first time,
because of that connection,

00:54:24.620 --> 00:54:28.570
because of that ability
to fund directly,

00:54:28.570 --> 00:54:33.550
radio producers like
myself are able to get by.

00:54:33.550 --> 00:54:38.740
And it was really touch-and-go
there for a while.

00:54:38.740 --> 00:54:43.700
I was really trying to leave
radio about seven years ago,

00:54:43.700 --> 00:54:45.490
right after the kids were born.

00:54:45.490 --> 00:54:48.180
I did everything in my
power to leave radio,

00:54:48.180 --> 00:54:52.660
because it just seemed like a
selfish choice for my family.

00:54:52.660 --> 00:54:57.030
And so Kickstarter was just
a huge game changer for me.

00:54:57.030 --> 00:54:58.780
I owe them everything.

00:54:58.780 --> 00:55:02.180
I think it's one of the
most interesting disruptive

00:55:02.180 --> 00:55:06.910
technologies, to overuse
an overused term, that's

00:55:06.910 --> 00:55:08.530
available.

00:55:08.530 --> 00:55:11.970
And it was super important
to creative people like me.

00:55:11.970 --> 00:55:16.010
LOGAN URY: I think it's nice
to end on a point of gratitude.

00:55:16.010 --> 00:55:17.800
Thank you so much for coming.

00:55:17.800 --> 00:55:20.250
ROMAN MARS: Thank you so much.

